commentBody:
@Steve L 

It took me a few minutes more than Thursday, but yesterday was one of my fastest Thursdays ever. 

I did think this was on the easy side for Friday, but I got a little hung up with a typo in OCTO that left me wondering who the oft-recorded jazz bassist RiN Carter was.

@Adam 

Both clever clues, but you won't find either on Lewis's list on Monday, as neither one is a debut.  In fact, the IGLOO clue has appeared four times, and once more in the plural.  The ESSAYS clue has appeared three times, with one other in the singular.

The fact that at least 26 people agree with you is proof that people forget, new people pick up the habit, and that a good clue is a good clue, even if not an original one.

@john ezra

Apologies to Cole Porter, you mean. He had a way with a lyric. 

But yours was excellent!

@Mike 
Holy Toledo!  You really can pound them out.

I centigram cracker to the emus as a bribe.

@Mike 

Ounce upon a time I thought these puns too heavy, now I bow to the incredible lightness of being Mike, up pound my word, I do. 


🏆

@Marshall Walthew 

“Get Shorty” is probably the only ELMORE Leonard novel I have read. I enjoyed it and I don’t know why I haven’t read more of his stuff. 

That said, I wouldn’t have minded seeing ELMORE James in the puzzle. He was a fantastic blues guitarist who should be as well known as B.B. King or Muddy Waters.

@Marshall Walthew 
I met him once when he spoke at the Tucson Festival of Books. I was a volunteer there.
A very kind, gracious,  and thoughtful man.

@Patrick J. 
Yup, photo was taken on 3/12/2021 on the set of Opera Australia’s Tosca at the Sydney Opera House. Opera Australia opened its stage to the public for a one-off life drawing class. Sorry, the caption of the column’s picture is accurate.  Thanks for not adding  “Just say’n”.

<a href="http://tinyurl.com//2xut3r8e" target="_blank">http://tinyurl.com//2xut3r8e</a>

@Rich in Atlanta 

Well, you got me.  At first, I thought you meant that your wife was Black, which might be puzzling to some good ol' boys down below the Mason-Dixon, but then it occurred to me that Morehouse is a men's college.

So, care to elaborate?

@Holland Oats 

Maybe, but it would also be an easier clue.

In my opinion, this puzzle was already on the easy side for a Friday, so maybe that's why it wasn't "high" time for that clue.

@Helen Wright 

Many years ago, that same word (ESSAYS) was clued as "Lamb pieces" and "Lamb products".

As it becomes harder and harder to find a clever new clue for a word which, along with its singular form, appears hundreds of times, I'd expect those clues to resurface someday soon.

@Barry Ancona 

Oops. I made much the same comment because I hadn’t seen yours. 

Sorry.

@John 

The clue was "Jardín contents," not "Jardin contents," (look very closely), which makes it Spanish, not French.

(From a fluent Spanish speaker and a so-so French speaker.)

@Jim 

My time was exactly the same as my Wednesday average. 




>>>

@Jeff Z 

Yes, and what about apes?  A whole planet full of those. Did you honestly think that was really Roddy McDowell?


Hybrid from a cat and a bird?  An emeow.

@Jeff Z

Make that First, and so far only known to humans anyway…

Let’s not assume what other species know or don’t know. Sorry to nitpick. Oh, there I go with a monkey slur of my own…

@Ivy 
The Valentine's day puzzle was way harder than a usual Wednesday puzzle, so as a treat we get an easy Friday!

(Gluten free cookies for the emus!)

@John 
Not-so-fond memories of driving through your state, and stopping at all the toll plazas, pre-EZ Pass. Sure, you could hop onto Route 17, but that was not a time saver.

Side note: in Harry Potter, Stan Shunpike is the driver of the magical Night Bus, which does not rely on conventional roadways. Thanks, now I get it.

@Bonnie 

Hasn't actually started snowing yet but the sky has that white-gray look and the air smells like snow!

Hoping for a couple inches....

@Leah 

I'm going to go out on a limb and guess you haven't been doing crosswords very long, because NENE is one of the most blatant examples of crosswordese there is.  It has appeared 316 times, although not for about 8 months (7/2/23), clued as the goose at least 90% of the time.  One of my favorite clues was 1/11/20, "Double birdie?"

In real life, it's a rare bird, but in crosslandia, it's as common as a pigeon in Central Park.

@Deadline 
I wanted to put HAMM, because a monkey named Ham was also sent into space, by the US.

But it was a suborbital flight, so congrats to whoever wrote this terrific clue.

@kilaueabart 

The musical SPAMALOT is based on the movie “Monty Python and the Holy Grail.” Maybe that’s more familiar? 

YOO-HOO is a chocolate soda introduced in 1928. I’m not sure if it’s available all over the US.
